Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>graund</i>, <i>graunt</i> ‘tall, large’ (Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i>, from Latin <i>grandis</i>), given either to a person of remarkable size, or else in a relative way to distinguish two bearers of the same personal name, often representatives of different generations within the same family.","English: from the rare Middle English (and Old English) personal name <i>Grante</i> or <i>Grente</i>.","Irish: in Ireland this is usually the Norman Scottish name (see 1 above), but it was also adopted for Irish <b>Mag Raighne</b>, see   Graney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Graney","meanings":["Irish (Galway, Cork, and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Raighne</b> ‘son of <i>Raighne</i>’, a pet form of <i>Raghnall</i>. It has sometimes been changed to   Grant  . See also   Rainey  .","Possibly an altered form of Swiss German <b>Gräni</b>, unexplained."]},{"name":"Grand","meanings":["French: nickname from Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i> ‘tall, large’, from Latin <i>grandis</i>. See also   Grant   1 and 4, compare   Degrand   and   Legrand  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived in a gravelly area, from Middle Low German <i>grand</i> ‘coarse gravel’.","German: nickname from a southern word of uncertain origin meaning ‘frustration, anger, ire’."]},{"name":"Grande","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Rocco, Domenic, Mario, Antonio, Santo, Orlando, Americo, Carmine, Gennaro, Luigi, Pasquale, Saverio, Alberico.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Alicia, Ricardo, Jorge, Juan, Raul, Angel, Atilio.","Italian, Spanish, and Portuguese: nickname for someone of large stature, in either a literal or figurative sense, from <i>grande</i> ‘tall, large’.","German: habitational name from Grande in Holstein or Grand in Bavaria."]},{"name":"General","meanings":["African American: from the English vocabulary word <i>general</i>, possibly adopted as a surname in honor of a certain general of the US army, most probably Ulysses S. Grant (see   Grant  , compare   President  ). Compare also 3 below.","German: nickname for a mercenary (employed in royal services).","Hispanic (mainly Philippines): nickname from Spanish <i>general</i> ‘general’ (military officer)."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":10,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":23,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":32,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":77,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne Grant was born about 1305, in Shipton, Shropshire, England, her father, Philippe le Grant, was 27 and her mother, Mrs. Philippi le Grant, was 25. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with William Bowdler. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1305–":"umbes 1305–Surnud","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1332–Female":"1332–Surnud","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1281–Female":"1281–Surnud","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","about 1305":"umbes 1305","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hope Bowdler, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hope Bowdler, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shipton, Shropshire, England":"Shipton, Shropshire, England","Church Stretton, Shropshire, England":"Church Stretton, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1305–":"noin 1305–Kuollut","1305–Female":"1305–Kuollut","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1332–Female":"1332–Kuollut","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1337–Male":"1337–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1281–Female":"1281–Kuollut","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","about 1305":"noin 1305","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","about 1330":"noin 1330","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hope Bowdler, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hope Bowdler, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shipton, Shropshire, England":"Shipton, Shropshire, England","